[32m│[0m 1.0 (Flag captured and verified)                                             [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m ### thoughts                                                                 [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m The vulnerability is a classic JWT "none algorithm" attack. The application  [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m uses JWT tokens with `alg: none`, which means no signature validation        [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m occurs. This allows an attacker to:                                          [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m 1. Decode the base64 payload                                                 [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m 2. Modify the role claim from "user" to "admin"                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m 3. Re-encode and send the tampered token                                     [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m 4. Gain unauthorized admin privileges                                        [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m The attack chain was:                                                        [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m - Login → Get user token → Modify role → Access admin page → Get flag        [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m This is a critical authentication bypass vulnerability that completely       [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m compromises the application's access control mechanism. The flag was         [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m successfully extracted using this privilege escalation technique.            [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
